<DOCNO> AP900725-0004 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
an african national congress 
leader who returned from exile under a government grant of immunity 
has reportedly been detained by police for questioning in an 
investigation of guerrilla activities an anc spokesman said 
thursday 
chief anc spokesman ahmed kathrada said he received information 
from a reliable source wednesday night about the detention of mac 
maharaj a fellow member of the ancs 35person national executive 
committee 
maharaj who is affiliated with the south african communist 
party was among the first of the exiled anc leaders to return to 
south africa this spring after the whiteminority government 
legalized the black nationalist movement he had worked at the 
ancs exile headquarters in lusaka zambia 
president fw de klerk granted temporary immunity from 
prosecution to members of the ancs executive committee to allow 
them to return to the country for negotiations the immunity 
covered past offenses but not activities considered illegal since 
the exiles return 
kathrada would not reveal the source for his information about 
maharajs detention but described it as reliable 
dozens of anc guerrillas who recently infiltrated the country 
have been arrested according to south african press reports 
police say they have seized weapons including grenade launchers 
mines and combat rifles 
many of those arrested are being held under the internal 
security act which allows indefinite detention without trial 
kathrada said the anc will discuss the recent wave of arrests 
with the government and reiterated his organizations objections to 
the internal security act 
police spokesmen were unable early thursday to confirm the 
report of maharajs arrest they have not named any of the others 
detained for questioning in the investigation of anc guerrilla 
activities 
the ancs internal chairman walter sisulu has said that 150 anc 
members have been arrested recently and that the detentions go 
against the spirit of the talks held between the anc and the 
government in may 
the anc has confirmed that its guerrillas continue to infiltrate 
south africa but denies police and media reports of an anc plot to 
seize power if political negotiations fail 
 
the anc supports a guerrilla campaign against the whiteled 
government but it has not carried out any major attacks this year 
 
the anc the countrys leading black opposition group says it 
will not suspend or call off its ineffective armed struggle until a 
formal treaty is negotiated with the government 
 
de klerk has rejected demands by conservative whites that he 
break off talks with the anc because of the reported guerrilla 
activities 
de klerk says he will meet aug 6 with nelson mandela and other 
top anc leaders to try and clear the way for negotiations on 
sharing political power with the black majority 
 
the anc says that before formal constitutional negotiations can 
begin the government must allow 20000 anc exiles to return without 
fear of arrest and release some 3000 people convicted of 
politically motivated crimes on wednesday night mandela praised 
thousands of armed men and boys for defending their neighborhoods 
in a township where at least 21 people died this week in fighting 
between black factions 
you have the support of the anc in everything that you do 
the leader of the african national congress told the crowd of 
2000 who waved spears axes sticks and chairlegs and chanted 
anc in the township of sebokeng 
mandela pleaded for sebokeng to return to normal after three 
days of fighting arson street blockades work and school boycotts 
residents and police say at least 21 people died sunday after 
members of the zulubased inkatha party headed by mangosuthu 
buthelezi staged a rally in sebokeng south of johannesburg 
armed inkatha members left the rally and clashed with township 
residents who were warned for days by anc leaders that inkatha 
planned to attack them fighting continued sporadically tuesday 
night and spread to neighboring evaton 
mandela deputy president of the anc said sebokeng was an anc 
stronghold and blamed the violence on inkatha we are happy to 
note that you made a stand against the thugs and killers who came 
from outside in order to kill our people he told the angry crowd 
of young blacks 
the inkatha vs anc violence has killed 5000 people in natal 
province the past five years the sebokeng battle was the worst 
outbreak of the feud outside natal 
both the anc and inkatha oppose apartheid but differ on ways to 
fight racial segregation in south africa 
</TEXT>
