<DOCNO> AP900725-0006 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the two koreas signed a historic 
agreement thursday setting up the first meetings between prime 
ministers of the hostile states since the korean peninsula was 
divided more than 40 years ago 
the 19point agreement calls for meetings in seoul from sept 
47 to discuss the easing of political and military confrontations 
multilateral exchanges and cooperation on the divided peninsula 
a second meeting is to be held in the communist north korean 
capital of pyongyang from oct 1619 
this precious fruit will open a decisive chapter in a road to 
ending national division and achieving peaceful unification said 
song hanho the chief south korean delegate 
we can no longer shun the changing international situation 
he said we should rather actively respond to this and use it as 
an opportunity to pursue national prosperity and forging a new 
history 
representatives of both countries signed the agreement in the 
truce village of panmunjom inside the 2milewide demilitarized 
zone separating the two koreas 
later thursday five north koreans arrived on the northern side 
of the border presumably in preparation to cross into south korea 
a delay in their arrival however was first blamed on bad 
weather and later on lastminute meetings south korean officials 
finally said there were indications the crossing might be called 
off but they did not elaborate 
the north koreans would be the first to cross the border with 
the approval of both governments since 1985 when dozens of 
separated family members were allowed brief reunions 
the north koreans were scheduled to take part in a twoday 
conference with south korean opposition activists to discuss plans 
for an unprecedented joint rally calling for unification of their 
divided peninsula both nations desire unification but on their own 
terms 
three south korean dissidents were allowed into the border 
security area to wait for the north koreans while dozens of others 
prepared to welcome them a few miles away 
lets become one nation and tear down the iron wall of 
division read placards at the welcome site about 100 radical 
students sang solidarity songs while awaiting the north koreans 
twelve riot police buses were parked in the area but police 
remained out of sight 
south korean dissidents said the unification rally was expected 
to be held in panmunjom on aug 15 a sentimental holiday on both 
sides of the border celebrating the 1945 liberation of korea after 
35 years of japanese colonial rule 
the rally would mark the first contact between civilian 
organizations of the two koreas in the past south korean 
authorities have blocked such contacts out of fear they could turn 
into radical antigovernment protests 
the planned prime ministers meetings and the unification rally 
could serve as indicators of the future course of relations between 
communist north korea and prowestern south korea bitter enemies 
for more than four decades 
the korean peninsula was divided after world war ii and two 
separate governments were formed in 1948 north and south korea 
fought a threeyear war that ended in 1953 no peace treaty has 
been signed and they are still technically at war 
by signing the accord for a prime ministers meeting north korea 
grants tacit recognition to the legitimacy of the seoul government 
a recognition denied since 1948 
prime ministers kang younghoon of south korea and yon hyung muk 
of north korea are considered figureheads in their respective 
governments with limited policymaking roles 
but their meeting is symbolically significant because it would 
be the highestlevel contacts ever between the two rival states 
the most powerful figures in the two countries are president roh 
taewoo of south korea and kim il sung the north korean president 
and communist leader 
despite sporadic talks on exchanges and easing tension there 
has been little real progress in improving relations between the 
koreas 
the korean border is one of the most heavily fortified in the 
world more than 15 million troops are deployed on both sides 
there is no mail travel or other communication between the two 
sides 
last week roh proposed that the border be opened for five days 
in midaugust on a trial basis allowing people on both sides free 
travel 
north korea rejected rohs proposal but has said it is willing 
to open the border on a limited basis on aug 15 to koreans 
desiring unification the north also demanded that seoul scrap its 
anticommunist national security laws and release prisoners jailed 
for promoting unification 
</TEXT>
