<TEXT>
david souters start in upholding the law 
came at concord high school where classmates pegged the popular 
member of the hall traffic squad as destined for bigger and better 
things 
their prediction has proven true souter is a senate 
confirmation away from one of the nations highest honors a seat 
on the supreme court 
yet it appears his meteoric rise in the legal community has done 
little to change the man whom classmate john prowse remembers from 
his traffic squad days 
i guess that was the first enforcement duty that he had and 
let me tell you he was good at it prowse said in an interview 
tuesday 
soutie as souters classmates called him still lives in 
the same house he grew up in a modest clapboard and shingled 
building tucked away on a tiny dirt road in weare a town of 4500 
people a dozen miles from concord 
and judging from the praise being heaped on him from fellow 
lawyers and judges he is viewed no differently now than 33 years 
ago when concords class of 57 voted him most sophisticated most 
literary and most likely to succeed 
the life of the 50yearold bachelor now is most likely to be 
dissected as the senate prepares for confirmation hearings and 
interest groups involved in the abortion debate and other 
contentious issues scour souters record for hints of how he might 
vote as a supreme court justice 
friends and associates say people will find that souter the man 
is much like souter the boy modest considerate frugal 
studious humorous and anything but controversial he has a small 
circle of friends choosing instead to spent much of his time 
alone studying and interpreting the law his breaks for recreation 
are spent hiking the hills and mountains of new hampshire his home 
since age 11 
im very happy to go off alone souter once said 
prowse remembers his boyhood friend as one of the rare people 
who transcended all the cliques in high school we called them the 
jocks and the brains back then everyone thought very highly of 
him 
he was an honor student student council member and yearbook 
staffer beginning his lifelong hobbies of collecting books and 
stamps while gaining a reputation as an intellectual 
friends say souter balances his bookwormish image with a biting 
sense of humor 
on one of his few notsogood days at high school a teacher 
returned a paper to souter with the admonition it was so bad he 
should take it home and wrap the garbage with it prowse says 
im not in the habit of wrapping my garbage in bond paper 
was souters quick retort according to prowse who said his friend 
meant no disrespect but often used his dry wit to break up school 
monotony 
prowse laughs today at a yearbook reference that souter enjoyed 
giving and attending scandalous parties 
this was the 1950s when scandalous meant that the parents 
werent home prowse said pot then was something you put on 
the stove and grass was something that you mowed and most of us 
didnt have our first beer until we were in the military or 
sophomores in college 
friends now say souter rarely stays long at social functions 
generally saying he needs to go home to work thats where the 
white house found him sunday tucked away in the house that could 
easily be mistaken for vacant its mailbox listing to the left its 
paint chipping and a doghouse out back all but overrun with high 
grass 
his love of the outdoors is easily understandable the roads 
leading to the house offer a stunning view of the states rolling 
hills the nighttime sky is breathtaking 
souters dedication to his work friends say can be traced to 
his youth when he often lingered so long at new hampshire 
historical society exhibits that he had to be asked to leave 
he exhibited similar commitment during stints as an overseer of 
dartmouth medical school and as a board member and president of 
concord hospital colleagues say 
i never worked so hard in my life than when he was here 
said the hospitals current president richard warner but while 
serving as master of ceremonies for a retirement party souter 
displayed the most fantastic dry sense of humor that you can 
imagine 
souter lived with his mother most of his life but she now 
resides in nearby concord in a retirement home now 82 she takes 
his confirmation for granted and says she will miss his frequent 
visits 
the nomination has brought a gush of pride to new hampshire 
at cinders country store a few miles from souters home an 
outdoor sign promoting the pizza was rearranged tuesday so a new 
message could be added in the middle good luck david souter 
</TEXT>
