<TEXT>
president bushs first appointment to the 
supreme court and the speed of the announcement are helping him 
score points with conservatives and moderates while temporarily 
defusing the emotional abortion argument 
moderates generally seem comfortable with the fact that david h 
souter although billed as a conservative has left no paper trail 
yet as a federal appeals court judge particularly on the abortion 
issue 
and conservatives seem to be rejoicing in the mere fact that 
souter came with a strong recommendation from white house chief of 
staff john sununu 
since sununu is the republican right wings unofficial liaison 
with the white house his seal of approval must mean that souters 
conservative credentials are impeccable the reasoning goes 
and while bush has sought to minimize sununus role in souters 
selection senior white house officials suggest privately that the 
former new hampshire governors role was one of direct advocacy for 
the man he placed on his state supreme court in 1983 
bushs quick naming of souter caught abortion rights activists 
and opponents off guard cutting off any efforts on their part to 
mount massive prenomination lobbying campaigns 
but at the same time some white house officials privately have 
voiced concern that the presidents rapid naming of souter mainly 
with only sununu vouching for him has shortcircuited the system 
of elaborate background checks 
although his background was routinely checked when he was 
nominated earlier this year to the federal appeals court in boston 
he as yet has not received the degree of scrutiny to which other 
highlevel appointees have been subject 
and while souters lifestyle seems spartan and his judicial 
views seem strict constructionist some administration 
conservatives suggest there is a high potential for surprise once 
souter is on the bench 
bush for the time being seems to be having it both ways with the 
appointment not alienating either conservatives or moderates and 
it isnt the first time his administration has been able to gloss 
over a controversial subject and appease rival wings of the party 
at the same time 
for instance vice president dan quayle often seem at odds with 
bush on issues involving relations with the soviet union taking a 
harderline stand 
when that happens spokesmen for both bush and quayle quickly 
insist the two leaders are on the same wavelength when in fact 
quayles words have been mainly designed for conservative audiences 
sununu has been known to practice the same verbal 
sleightofhand 
for instance shortly after bush entered budget negotiations 
pledging there were no preconditions sununu was putting out 
the word that the president likely would reject any tax proposal 
made by democrats 
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater disavowed sununus 
comments saying they didnt reflect the views of the president 
but was sununu in the doghouse not on your life his words were 
designed to provide a reassuring signal to conservatives that the 
president wasnt about to abandon his opposition to new taxes 
of course that was before bush specifically revoked his no 
new taxes pledge 
on the abortion issue bush has managed to soften some of the 
edges of his position even as he asserts that hes strongly 
antiabortion 
bush says he opposes government funding for any abortions other 
than those to save the life of the mother but he also says that if 
there isnt government money involved supports a womans right to 
abortion in cases of rape or incest 
earlier in his career bush voiced support for the roe vs wade 
supreme court ruling that he now says he would like to see 
overturned 
there has always been a perception among some womens groups 
that first lady barbara bush does not share her presidents 
antiabortion views 
she declines to address the issue but her silence only 
reinforces that perception and further blurs the edges of bushs 
stance 
this may have helped bush escape some of the vitriol that 
prochoice activists have directed at other political leaders 
including former president reagan who oppose abortion rights 
in the same way sununus role in the selection of souter for 
the supreme court is enabling bush to escape criticism from 
antiabortion activists who would have preferred a candidate with a 
proven judicial antiabortion record 
meanwhile bush has said his position has not changed on 
abortion at least since the last time he changed it 
but his record for standing by a position no longer has much 
credibility even with republican audiences since his aboutface 
on no new taxes 
a gop audience in philadelphia laughed on tuesday when he said 
he was going to leave before the broccoli was served but it howled 
and applauded when he added im going to stay with my position 
you know i never change my position on anything 
