<TEXT>
it was a night of anomaly at the mostly mozart 
festival 
a cambridgeeducated musician conducted haydns oxford 
symphony a mozart piano concerto was played with cadenzas nearly 
200 years older than it a clarinetist of remarkable talent showed 
himself to be his own worst enemy 
the concert tuesday also raised an important issue how a 
performers interpretation can cross the border into arrogance 
the conductor was mark elder and he was joined by belfastborn 
pianist barry douglas in the piano concerto no 22 in eflat k 
482 and richard stoltzman in mozarts a major clarinet concerto 
k 622 
stoltzman 48 a fixture at mostly mozart for more than a 
decade has joined that rare species a windplaying superstar 
like jeanpierre rampal heinz holliger or james galway in demand 
with concertbookers and a guaranteed sellout 
he is unquestionably one of the great clarinet players known 
for his ability to play incredibly softly his smooth articulation 
his technique 
but many clarinetists dislike him intensely whether it be 
jealousy distaste at his crossover into jazz wide vibrato which 
is unusual for a clarinetist or highly personal interpretations 
in the mozart concerto tuesday his little additions of ornament 
were reasonably tasteful the large size of avery fisher hall 
smoothed over his vibrato his excessive tonguing of fast notes was 
acceptable though sometimes distracting 
but stoltzmans taffychewing distortion of rhythm in an attempt 
to be expressive was so severe that the music lost shape lines 
didnt unfurl they jerked back and forth obscured by the 
soloists shadow mozart lost even the orchestra seemed tentative 
at times 
but another anomaly stoltzman played the slow movement one of 
mozarts greatest with surpassing serenity he was simple to the 
point and communicated directly with the audience 
but stoltzman again trying to be different broke the spell 
with an ungainly inappropriate sounding cadenza instead of the one 
mozart wrote for his clarinet quintet also in a major which is 
traditionally played here 
cadenzas also figured prominently in the piano concerto they 
were by benjamin britten and had elements of rachmaninoff and 
debussy despite the clash of periods they are wonderful and 
somehow fitting and the 29yearold douglas seemed to play them 
with particular affinity 
douglas arrived after winning the 1986 tchaikovsky competition 
in moscow as the first nonrussian since van cliburn and also is 
given to unusual interpretations he played the concerto with a 
good deal of romance inflecting phrases in a personal but not 
excessive way 
the conductor kept the orchestra in extremely close ensemble 
with soloist elder director of the english national opera 
appropriately let the winds sing out a good course in a concerto 
which is really chamber music for piano strings and winds 
unlike stoltzman douglas seemed weaker in the soulful slow 
movement his melodies having a toodreamy almost formless 
quality there was some particularly fine interplay with the 
orchestra in the final rondo douglas seemed really to be 
listening in all it was a highlevel if not superlative 
performance 
in the succeeding symphony no 92 in g major nicknamed the 
oxford elder brought out a larger range of colors than is 
usually heard in haydn and better balanced the orchestras 
sections 
