<TEXT>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan 
seeking to reassure jittery financial markets says the central 
bank wont fritter away the gains made in the last few years in 
the fight against inflation 
greenspan told lawmakers tuesday that the fed has not abandoned 
its inflation battle as part of some deal with the bush 
administration to trim the federal budget deficit 
he insisted that any move to lower interest rates to ward off 
the adverse impacts of budget cuts and tax increases needed to 
reduce the deficit would be made only in the context of not 
inducing inflationary pressures 
private economists saw greenspans comments as an effort to calm 
fears in financial markets that the fed is buckling to 
electionyear pressures by the administration to abandon its 
inflation battle 
elliott platt director of economic research at donaldson 
lufkin amp jenrette said greenspans comments should help to ease 
market anxieties 
it took away from any negatives he created when he seemed to 
be wavering last week platt said 
those fears were raised when greenspan said the fed stood ready 
to lower interest rates to support a credible deficit reduction 
package if such assistance was needed to keep the country out of a 
recession 
at a hearing tuesday by the house banking subcommittee on 
domestic monetary policy rep stephen neal dnc told greenspan 
that he believed mondays steep drop in the stock market was caused 
by general worries that the fed was wavering in its 
inflationfighting resolve 
the dow jones industrial average finished down 5644 points on 
monday after a topsyturvy day that saw the indicator down by more 
than 100 points in early trading on tuesday stocks rebounded with 
the dow industrials finishing up by 1782 points 
in his testimony greenspan repeated his support for legislation 
sponsored by neal that would commit the fed to pursuing policies to 
achieve zero inflation he said he believed such a goal was 
within reach because of policies over the past three years that 
have slowed the growth of the nations money supply 
the feds goal is to provide enough money to the banking system 
to keep the economy growing while guarding against supplying so 
much that it results in renewed inflation over the past three 
years the money supply has grown at a slow pace not seen in three 
decades greenspan said 
if we dont fritter away the benefits of the last 2 to three 
years and i can assure you we dont intend to do that then i see 
no reason to expect other than the achievement of general price 
stability over the next several years greenspan told neal 
greenspan said the actual response of the fed to any 
deficitcutting agreement would depend very much on how financial 
markets viewed the package 
he predicted that a credible and enforceable budget deficit 
agreement would spark a significant drop in interest rates on 
financial markets and he said the fed would not act to accelerate 
the move to lower rates unless such action could be taken without 
risking the central banks overriding goal of reducing inflation 
greenspan testified that the recent report showing that consumer 
prices jumped 05 percent in june had added a note of caution 
to the inflation outlook 
but he said the june increase and other bad inflation figures 
reflected past history and not recent gains the fed has made by 
slowing the growth of the money supply 
