<TEXT>
when a judge began releasing demonstrators 
who had trespassed at the seabrook nuclear power plant in 1977 
thenattorney general david souter jumped into his car sped to the 
court and insisted the protesters be jailed 
when state workers struck illegally in 1983 thensuperior court 
judge souter agreed to a midnight hearing and issued a predawn 
ruling threatening stiff fines if the workers didnt end their 
sickout 
when a lawyer stole money from a client judge souter wanted him 
to go to jail not just repay the money 
throughout his career as prosecutor and judge in new hampshire 
souter 50 has taken his role seriously and dealt firmly with 
those who didnt hold the law in as high a regard as he 
the opinions he authored as a state supreme court justice reveal 
a writer who sticks to the facts and avoids rhetorical flourishes 
there are no broad pronouncements on issues such as abortion or 
affirmative action that he certainly would confront if he wins 
confirmation to the us supreme court 
souter was attorney general when the state police arrested 1414 
demonstrators who defied authorities marched onto the seabrook 
nuclear plant construction site and camped overnight 
the protesters were locked in national guard armories for two 
weeks when a local judge released a demonstrator on a suspended 
sentence and small fine souter was incensed 
he played a very significant role said seabrook foe robert 
cushing one of those arrested in the may 1977 protest 
cushing said that when souter found out about the suspended 
sentence he left from concord drove down to district court and 
argued that there should be a jail sentence imposed 
the judge resentenced the demonstrator cushing said 
the state employees association felt souters sting during a 
sickout in june 1983 at midnight thengov john sununu called 
souter and asked him to hold a hearing which he did at 345 am 
souter ordered everyone back to work and threatened to fine the 
union 5000 a day and its leadership 500 a day 
he came down heavy said the union director denis parker 
theres no question about it 
manchester lawyer jack middleton remembers a case in which a 
lawyer had stolen money from a client both sides had decided to 
drop the matter if the lawyer repaid the money he said but souter 
wouldnt buy it 
that just sounded like a bank transaction to him middleton 
said and he didnt view that as a loan 
in addition to showing that souter was tough middleton said the 
episode showed that souter was going to take a hard look at the 
facts and make up his own mind and not just take the word of 
the prosecution or the defense lawyer 
souter served seven years on the new hampshire supreme court 
in a 1988 decision criticized by womens rights groups souter 
ordered a new trial for a man who was convicted of sexual assault 
the defendant said his lawyers improperly were prevented from 
offering evidence the woman publicly flirted with other men on the 
day of the alleged attack 
souter said such evidence was essential to the mans defense 
that the woman had consented to having sex with him 
souter often sides with positions advanced by state government 
officials especially in criminal cases but there have been 
notable exceptions 
in 1988 souter led the state court in declaring 
unconstitutional a state law that barred a nonprofit group from 
providing legal services to some disabled people 
as state attorney general it fell to souter to defend the 
states prosecution of a couple who for religious purposes taped 
over the live free or die motto on their automobile license 
the supreme court ruled that the prosecution violated the couples 
religious freedom 
as a judge souter participated in just one known case dealing 
with abortion siding with the majority in a 1986 ruling that said 
physicians have a responsibility to test unborn children for birth 
defects and in the event defects are detected to counsel the 
pregnant woman about options including abortion 
