<TEXT>
physicians with aids are unlikely to transmit the 
deadly virus to patients during surgery according to a study of 
2160 people operated on by a tennessee doctor who had the disease 
none of the patients whom dr harold dennison operated on 
between 1982 and his 1989 death are believed to have contracted 
aids during surgery a report in this weeks journal of the 
american medical association said 
only one patient an intravenous drug user who frequented 
prostitutes tested positive for the aids virus but the authors 
concluded that the patient had contracted aids through his 
highrisk activities and not from surgical contact with dennison 
who removed a lymph node from the man in 1984 
the results of this investigation support the concept that 
risks to patients operated on by surgeons infected with the aids 
virus are most likely quite low wrote the authors led by dr 
ban mishu of the centers for disease control in atlanta 
an accompanying editorial by dr frank rhame a university of 
minnesota aids expert estimates that hundreds of aidsinfected 
surgeons are practicing in the united states 
the cdc has no figures on the number of us surgeons and 
physicians infected with aids said spokeswoman gayle lloyd 
but of the 139765 aids cases reported in the united states 
since 1981 more than 5000 involved healthcare workers including 
doctors nurses lab technicians and other medical workers she 
said 
but rhame said there are no known surgeontopatient 
transmissions of the disease he estimated the risk of patients 
being infected by their surgeons at between one in 100000 and one 
in 1 million operations 
dennison 56 died jan 30 1989 just weeks after he tested 
positive for aids dennison believed he contracted aids while 
operating on a patient with the disease but he didnt know when he 
had been infected coauthor dr william schaffner of vanderbilt 
universitys school of medicine said in a telephone interview 
tuesday 
it was estimated that dennison had been infected no earlier than 
1982 so with the help from baptist hospital hca west side 
hospital and hca park view hospital the nashville facilities 
where he worked the authors learned the names and addresses of 
the 2160 patients he had operated on since then 
none of them had been reported to tennessees aids registry and 
264 had died none of the deaths were aidsrelated 
the authors mailed letters to the 1896 remaining patients 
seeking to have them tested for aids letters to 244 patients were 
returned marked address unknown 
of the 1652 who were contacted 615 were tested for aids 
although 1037 patients chose not to submit to tests those who 
were tested had undergone the most invasive operations or had been 
operated on most recently when dennison was the most contagious 
and thus faced the greatest risk of contracting the virus 
schaffner said 
aids or acquired immune deficiency syndrome cripples victims 
ability to fight infections it is passed through blood and other 
body fluids 
