<TEXT>
capt joseph hazelwood will try to 
hold on to his license as a ships master at a coast guard hearing 
to determine if he was guilty of negligence in the nations worst 
oil spill 
todays administrative law hearing comes just four months after 
the skipper of the exxon valdez was acquitted in alaska on similar 
charges 
the judge harry j gardner could elect to dismiss all charges 
revoke hazelwoods license or place him on probation according to 
the coast guard and hazelwoods lawyers no fine or prison term can 
be levied 
hazelwood was accused of breaking a coast guard rule by drinking 
alcohol within four hours of assuming command of his ship and 
leaving the ships bridge while the vessel was traveling through 
prince william sound 
he also was accused of leaving a crewman who did not have a 
required license in control of the bridge 
hazelwoods attorney michael chalos contended in a telephone 
interview tuesday that any drinking within four hours of sailing 
was unintentional because the ship left port an hour earlier than 
scheduled 
he argued the coast guard had waived its requirement that the 
person in control of the bridge have a pilotage license for prince 
william sound and said the coast guard did not adequately monitor 
the exxon valdez via radar 
the exxon valdez was en route from the alaskan port of valdez to 
long beach on march 24 1989 when it struck a charted reef gashed 
by jagged rocks the 987foot tanker spilled nearly 11 million 
gallons of alaska crude oil 
hazelwood was acquitted of being drunk and reckless but was 
convicted of one misdemeanor charge of negligent discharge of oil 
he was ordered to pay 50000 restitution and spend 1000 hours 
cleaning beaches at prince william sound he is appealing the 
verdict 
