<TEXT>
the 1986 contra supply plane crash that led to 
revelations of us involvement in the irancontra affair is at the 
center of a civil lawsuit that opened today against richard secord 
and a cialinked airline 
eugene hasenfus the sole survivor when sandinista forces shot 
down his c132 in nicaragua during a supply run has accused secord 
and southern air transport of misleading him and using planes that 
were wholly inadequate and dilapidated 
hasenfus who was captured by the government troops and held for 
three months is joined in the lawsuit by the family of wallace 
sawyer jr the copilot who died in the october 1986 crash 
jury selection began today with hasenfus expected to take the 
stand later in the day as the first witness secord also was 
present 
secord a retired air force major general pleaded guilty nov 8 
to lying to congressional investigators when he said he wasnt 
aware of any money that went to oliver norths benefit from the 
maze of companies he had used in the irancontra affair secord on 
jan 24 was sentenced to two years probation 
when the suit was filed in 1988 attorneys had estimated damages 
at 135 million but on tuesday the judge asked for more specific 
figures 
following the crash the reagan administration faced with 
evidence found in the plane acknowledged money was diverted from 
iran arms sales to the contra supply operation 
the suit says hasenfus was recruited in 1986 through the 
pennsylvania airline corporate air services and william cooper a 
southern air pilot 
