<TEXT>
fiji adopted a constitution today that 
guarantees native fijians a majority in both houses of a new 
parliament 
the constitution calls for the native fijians to be allocated 37 
of the 70 seats in a house of representatives and 24 of the 34 
senate seats 
the guaranteed majority has been a demand of the military which 
overthrew a coalition dominated by ethnic indians in 1987 the 
military said the coup was necessary to protect the rights of 
indigenous fijians 
native fijians and ethnic indians each comprise slightly less 
than half of the 720000 people in fiji an island nation in the 
south pacific 
indians were a majority before the coup which was followed by a 
second military takeover in 1987 but emigration has since depleted 
their numbers 
president ratu sir penaia ganilau a native fijian promulgated 
the document following cabinet approval calling it an historic 
and solemn duty and asking for national reconciliation 
he said in a nationally broadcast radio speech that the 
constitution would immediately take effect as the supreme law of 
the land he added that he hoped elections would be held next 
year 
indian leaders have branded the constitution as racist 
feudalistic and undemocratic and said they would boycott the 
planned elections 
the constitution has not yet been released publicly 
ganilau said the coups were the result of a growing sense of 
insecurity among native fijians because indians dominated commerce 
finance and industry 
it seems only fair and just that the fijian position should be 
strengthened in some areas to compensate for its weaknesses in 
others 
he called on indians who were brought to fiji by the british as 
indentured sugarplantation workers to set aside that memory 
along with their sense of grievance about the past 
join with the fijians in sharing the nations resources and 
participating fully in national life ganilau said 
the proclamation comes 2 years after the country was declared a 
republic the 1970 postindependence constitution was revoked 
following the second coup 
in late may new delhi said it would launch an international 
campaign against fiji over the new constitution fiji ordered the 
indian embassy closed and expelled its diplomats in retaliation 
new zealand prime minister geoffrey palmer recently criticized 
the constitution saying it would not improve strained bilateral 
relations 
