<TEXT>
the government today charged four people 
with plotting its overthrow it also released three lawyers who had 
been detained without charge in a crackdown on proponents of 
multiparty politics 
the us embassy welcomed the release of the three but it 
expressed hopes that other detainees would also soon be released 
we hope the cases of those remaining in custody can be resolved 
rapidly said an embassy spokesman 
kenyan law permits detention without charge or trial of 
individuals the government considers a threat to state security 
those charged were former detainees george anyona and ngotho 
kariuki rural ruling party official augustine kathangu and 
university lecturer edward oyugi 
the government accused them of taking part in a meeting whose 
participants had seditious intentions of overthrowing the kenyan 
government by unlawful means 
anyona a former parliamentarian and an economist and kathangu 
an official of the governing kenya african national union in embu 
were additionally charged with possessing seditious material 
the four had been held without charge since july 12 when they 
were arrested together at a nairobiarea pub 
those released were lawyers gitobu imanyara john khaminwa and 
mohamed ibrahim they could not be immediately reached for comment 
their detentions preceded a rally planned for july 7 in favor of 
a multiparty system police tried to block the rally which led to 
riots in nairobi and four other cities at least 28 people died and 
scores were injured 
human rights lawyer gibson kamau kuria was threatened with 
arrest during the crackdown but was sheltered by the us embassy 
which helped him safely leave kenya 
still in detention are former cabinet ministers charles rubia 
and kenneth matiba and raila odinga a businessman and the son of 
former vice president oginga odinga 
rubia and matiba were picked up by police july 4 and odinga was 
detained july 5 they are leading advocates of multiparty politics 
in kenya which is by law a oneparty state khaminwa represented 
rubia and matiba and was detained when he sought information about 
their whereabouts 
imanyara edited the nairobi law monthly magazine which served 
as a platform for the advocates of political pluralism in this east 
african nation 
ibrahim was a partner in a law firm that has represented 
individuals not in favor with the authorities 
rubia and matiba had been denied a state license to convene the 
planned july 7 rally but a crowd gathered anyway rioting began 
when police armed with wooden clubs and firing tear gas canisters 
dispersed the crowd 
president daniel arap moi and other kenyan leaders argue that 
more than one political party in the country would lead to tribal 
wars among the estimated 40 tribes 
the government gave no reason for the lawyers release however 
clergymen lawyers and foreign governments including the united 
states had severely criticized the detentions 
on thursday the international bar association switched the site 
of its biannual convention in september from nairobi to new york 
city and cited the recent detentions as one reason 
</TEXT>
