<TEXT>
many hospitals should routinely offer aids tests 
to all patients especially in poor city neighborhoods because so 
many people are unknowingly infected with the aids virus a 
government study recommends 
the chief author of the report said aids screening should become 
as common a part of hospital care as testing for heart disease and 
glaucoma 
there is a large number of infected persons who are unaware of 
their status said dr michael e st louis hospitals may be 
an efficient place where they could potentially get plugged into an 
appropriate program of treatment or counseling 
his report based on a major study by the us centers for 
disease control found that aids infections are extremely common in 
some poor city areas where one in five young and middleage men 
carry the virus but unsuspected aids infections occur virtually 
everywhere in the united states 
by failing to spot these infections the study said hospitals 
are missing an important opportunity to provide early care to 
people who are likely to develop grave illnesses while there is no 
cure for aids treatment early in the infection can delay the start 
of aidsrelated health problems 
st louis said that while ideally most hospitals would offer 
routine aids testing the screening should be done only if they are 
prepared to keep the results confidential and to offer followup 
counseling and care to people who turn out to be infected 
we are not saying that every hospital should be doing this 
he said but on the basis of our findings many may need to 
consider it 
while the cdc has not changed its estimate that 1 million 
americans are infected with the aids virus the latest study found 
a 70fold difference in the infection rate across the united states 
in most places the virus is still rare in several midwest and 
western states well under 1 percent of patients screened carried 
the virus by contrast at two hospitals in new york city and 
newark nj more than 5 percent of all patients were infected 
the numbers were especially high considering that the 
researchers did not test anyone who went to the hospital with any 
condition that might result from the aids virus or suggest a 
higherthanusual risk of catching it these included all people 
with cancer infections hemophilia psychiatric problems and 
gunshot wounds 
our findings yield no support for the premise that the aids 
epidemic will soon abate even in the areas that were the earliest 
infected such as the new york metropolitan area the doctors 
wrote 
their study published in thursdays new england journal of 
medicine was based on aids tests anonymously performed on 89547 
people their blood was drawn for other purposes at 26 hospitals 
during the past two years 
among the findings 
the overall aids infection rate ranged from less than onetenth 
of 1 percent to nearly 8 percent depending on the hospitals 
location the testing turned up at least one unsuspected infection 
in every hospital 
men were seven times more likely than women to carry the virus 
and blacks were almost twice as likely as whites to be infected 
at the two new york area hospitals with the highest infections 
the virus was most common among men between ages 25 to 44 about 20 
percent of them were infected 
at the eight hospitals with the lowest infection rates none of 
the 5002 women tested between ages 25 and 44 carried the virus 
dr deborah j cotton clinical director for aids at beth israel 
hospital in boston cautioned that keeping test results 
confidential can be a serious problem and often no counseling 
programs exist to advise people who find they are infected 
it would be wrong to offer the test if there is no place to 
refer patients to if they turn out to be positive she said 
st louis said the cdc is revising its formal guidelines on 
hospital screening to recommend more aggressive testing for the 
aids virus 
