<TEXT>
south carolinas statehouse which still 
bears the scars of shermans cannons is being shaken anew by a 
threering scandal that involves allegations of vote buying 
drunken driving and construction payoffs 
this has rocked the entire statehouse state rep david 
beasley said of the scandals he said he worried that the 
investigations would have longterm damaging effects on 
politics in the state 
gov carroll campbell a republican heavily favored for 
reelection this year also has said he worries about his states 
image 
we cant have south carolina across the nation looking like 
the way were being painted the governor said 
the allegations have called into question the states relatively 
lax laws regulating lobbying and campaign contributions 
the current laws are so permissive that people in south 
carolina feel you can do anything said john crangle head of the 
states chapter of common cause the government watchdog group 
two of the three investigations became public in the past week 
first federal officials confirmed they were looking into 
allegations of illegal conduct by state lawmakers lawmakers say a 
lobbyist working as an undercover agent offered legislators cash 
in exchange for votes 
then tuesday sources said the us justice department was 
looking into allegations that the states top fbi officer asked the 
chief highway patrolman to help him avoid a drunkendriving charge 
the fbi already was investigating the highway department on 
allegations that top officials took money from a leading contractor 
this is not good timing beasley said 
the cashforvotes investigation troubles lawmakers the most at 
the heart of it is ron l cobb a flashy cigarsmoking former 
legislator who is a wellknown lobbyist 
cobb some lawmakers said offered them cash this spring when 
lobbying them about a bill that would have allowed parimutuel 
betting a source has told the associated press that fbi agents 
videotaped the exchanges 
many lawmakers and lobbyists believe the investigation is a 
sting operation cobbs purported client a georgiabased 
organization called the alpha group does not exist according to 
georgia or south carolina records 
however neither us attorney bart daniel nor fred verinder 
the fbis top agent in south carolina will elaborate about the 
investigation cobb has not returned telephone calls to his office 
no one has been charged with a crime 
critics blame the investigation on south carolinas lax rules on 
lobbyists and campaign contributions 
for example south carolina has no limit on corporate or 
individual campaign contributions no limits on cash donations 
little regulation on gifts from lobbyists and no preelection 
campaign finance reports 
twentyseven states limit individual campaign contributions 35 
states either ban or limit corporate contributions 26 limit cash 
contributions and 15 ban or limit gifts from lobbyists and south 
carolina is among only three states that allow candidates to wait 
until after a general election to file their campaign finance 
reports 
furthermore the finance reports are sent to committees in the 
state house and senate which crangle said is like having the fox 
watch over the henhouse 
attempts at reform have died in recent years including this 
year when the general assembly failed to complete work on a bill 
that would have required lobbyists to verify more details about 
their spending 
state sen sherry martschink said news of the investigation 
actually pleases her 
it should signal the end of the grim days the end of shabby 
ethics legislation she said the revelations bring out into 
the open practices that should never have happened perhaps this is 
indeed the beginning of the end of the sad days 
but it is not apparently the end of the scandals verinder 
who is investigating the legislators is himself at the center of 
allegations involving a drunkendriving coverup 
government sources said on condition of anonymity that the 
justice departments office of professional responsibility would 
look into allegations that verinder was drunk when a trooper 
spotted his car weaving outside the city in late march 
after verinder was stopped the sources said he persuaded the 
trooper to let him call col jh red lanier the states chief 
highway patrolman lanier who denies any wrongdoing took verinder 
home verinder whose office said he would not comment was cited 
only with a speeding ticket 
he was drinking but he wasnt drunk lanier insisted 
he also denied that his actions had anything to do with an 
investigation of the highway department by the fbi and two other 
agencies the highway patrol is part of the highway department 
thats ridiculous lanier said he added that verinder 
cant control an investigation that the state law enforcement 
division the irs and the fbi that three agencies are doing 
the investigation is said to involve allegations that highway 
department employees took payoffs from contractors 
