sen dave durenberger today promised his 
colleagues to be a better man and then a better senator as 
they neared a vote on a resolution denouncing him for financial 
misconduct and ordering him to pay up to 123000 in restitution 
ethics committee chairman howell heflin dala said 
durenberger knowingly and willfully violated the established 
norms of senate behavior 
the evidence of knowing and willful misconduct is clear and 
convincing and far more troubling than senator durenbergers 
admitted negligence lack of wisdom or asserted misplaced reliance 
on others heflin told the senate 
every senator was expected to vote for the sanction except for 
durenberger and possibly his fellow minnesota republican sen rudy 
boschwitz said lois west durenbergers press secretary 
durenberger will vote present so as not to take a position 
west said boschwitz may vote the same way said his press 
secretary tim droogsma 
in prepared remarks scheduled for delivery on the floor after 
the vote durenberger called the senate action an ending and a 
beginning 
i ask your forgiveness he said for future challenges i 
need your friendship 
durenberger called the experience a costly education and 
assured senators i have reordered my personal and professional 
priorities to be first a better man and then a better senator 
as for the future i would ask only that i be judged not 
necessarily by what i say but what i do financial restitution is 
only a beginning 
