david h souters supreme court nomination has 
escaped harsh criticism so far even from groups inclined to 
oppose any bush nominee suggesting his lack of a record on 
divisive issues has insulated him from attack 
as the nominee toured capitol hill to meet with senators 
wednesday liberal groups said they hope the senate judiciary 
committee will closely question him during confirmation hearings in 
september but almost no one had bad words for him now 
on the right the only thing conservatives could find to worry 
about was the possibility that souter would prove to be other than 
one of their own 
richard a viguerie chairman of the united conservatives of 
america said most conservatives today have nervous smiles we 
think we can be happy but were a little apprehensive 
liberals though hardly celebrating were reluctant to attack 
the nomination 
ruth pratt of the national abortion rights action league in 
souters home state of new hampshire said the senate needs to 
find out his position on issues of privacy and choice we are 
somewhat encouraged by what we hear about his reluctance to 
overturn precedent 
marcus hurn spokesman for the new hampshire citizens alliance 
for gay and lesbian rights said he would testify in favor of 
souter if national gay rights groups oppose the nominee 
i dont think the white house is getting a very political 
judge hurn said i think he is a highly judicial person 
with a high regard for precedents 
sounding a warning though still not criticism faye wattleton 
of planned parenthood said if souter refuses to answer questions on 
abortion when he testifies before the senate judiciary committee 
probably in september i dont think he deserves to sit on the 
court 
rebecca hagelin of the conservative concerned women for america 
said were going to see an effort by extremist feminist 
organizations to bring about an abortion inquisition 
but she suggested that any group opposing his confirmation 
because he has not endorsed the high courts 1973 ruling legalizing 
abortion runs the risk of being branded extremist 
both liberal and conservative groups have acknowledged the 
president caught them off guard by picking a successor to william 
j brennan within three days of the supreme court justices 
retirement announcement 
by moving quickly and choosing someone apparently 
noncontroversial bush has accomplished the dual purpose of 
shortcircuiting a possible drive by opposing groups to influence 
the selection and enhancing confirmation prospects 
