<TEXT>
a jury was selected wednesday to decide a lawsuit 
that blames retired air force major general richard secord and a 
cialinked airline for the 1986 plane crash in nicaragua that 
helped unravel the irancontra affair 
cargo handler eugene hasenfus and the family of the planes 
copilot wallace sawyer jr claim in the lawsuit that secord and 
miamibased southern air transport used unsafe aircraft in the 
nicaraguan contra supply effort 
the october 1986 downing of the c123 by a sandinista rocket 
helped trigger the irancontra investigation after the crash the 
reagan administration acknowledged that money was diverted from 
iran arms sales to the contras despite a congressional ban on us 
military aid to the rebels 
a sixmember jury and two alternates were seated after 
questioning by senior us district judge c clyde atkins only a 
few of the 35 prospective jurors said they remembered reading or 
hearing about the crash none showed any recognition when former 
white house aide oliver north was mentioned as a possible witness 
secord sat at the defense table with southern air president 
william langton and a team of lawyers hasenfus of marinette 
wis sat across the room with his wife sally sawyers widow 
kasanee sawyer of magnolia ark and their attorneys 
secord pleaded guilty nov 8 to lying to the congressional 
committee investigating the irancontra affair and has been placed 
on two years probation 
when the lawsuit was filed in 1988 attorneys had estimated 
damages at 135 million however on wednesday the plaintiffs 
submitted new figures seeking actual damages of about 2 million 
for sawyers family and about 1 million for hasenfus 
hasenfus a cargo handler or kicker aboard a plane 
secretly supplying the nicaraguan rebels was captured and held for 
about three months after nicaraguan troops shot down the plane 
the lawsuit says hasenfus was recruited in 1986 through the 
pennsylvania airline corporate air services and william cooper a 
pilot for southern air which was once owned by the cia and 
continues to do contract work for the us government 
cooper who also died in the crash led hasenfus to believe he 
was working on behalf of the us government on a project being 
directed right out of the back door of the white house the 
lawsuit said 
southern air has denied any association with the hasenfus flight 
secords attorneys describe hasenfus as a mercenary paid about 
3000 a month who knew the risks 
</TEXT>
