<TEXT>
federal agencies studying the feasibility of 
highspeed trains propelled by magnets should know by 1993 whether 
the united states can regain the lead in this transportation 
technology said a report released wednesday 
the report a preliminary implementation plan developed by 
the army corps of engineers sets a timetable under which various 
federal agencies would evaluate and then oversee the development of 
magnetic levitation trains in the united states 
we believe there is a golden opportunity for magnetic 
levitation in this country said dan mauldin deputy director of 
civil works for the corps of engineers 
magnetic levitation trains are propelled by magnets on a cushion 
of air over a rail such trains could travel up to 300 miles per 
hour use less energy than conventional means of transportation and 
would be cheaper to ride than airplanes according to the report 
so far only the japanese and the germans have developed 
prototype trains several projects are under discussion in the 
united states 
in fiscal 1993 the federal agencies studying magnetic 
levitation which include the transportation department the 
federal railroad administration and the corps will choose from 
among three options according to the report 
the agencies may ask one or more industry teams to design an 
advanced magnetic levitation system the winning team would 
then have the opportunity to build and operate a fullscale 
prototype 
the agencies may encourage us industry to team with state and 
local interests to build several different magnetic levitation 
systems at different sites the market would then determine which 
system is superior based on operation maintenance and costs 
the agencies may encourage privatesector firms to adapt foreign 
magnetic levitation systems for us transportation needs the last 
option would require the smallest outlay of federal money the 
report noted 
magnetic levitation was invented and pioneered in the 1960s and 
1970s by americans including james powell and gordon danby at 
brookhaven national laboratory in new york but us advances 
stopped around 1974 when the federal role in magnetic levitation 
development ended sen daniel p moynihan said at a news 
conference to release the report 
</TEXT>
