<TEXT>
a chemical company warned former and current 
employees wednesday that a study shows for the first time a 
possible direct link between pancreatic cancer and the insecticide 
ddt 
the study by the university of michigan focused on 28 cases of 
pancreatic cancer among rohm amp haas employees who worked at its 
philadelphia plant from 1948 to 1971 when ddt and related 
chemicals were produced there 
other researchers expressed caution at the preliminary results 
saying too little was known to definitively draw a link between the 
chemical and pancreatic cancer the fifthleading cancer killer 
ddt is known to cause liver cancer at high doses in mice but is 
not known to cause cancer in humans said albert heier a us 
environmental protection agency spokesman the pesticide was banned 
in 1972 over concerns about its adverse effect on the environment 
and wildlife and its persistence in the food chain 
rohm amp haas spokesman george bochanski said the company received 
a draft of the study from dr david garabrant about two weeks ago 
and decided to release the results to its employees bochanski said 
the company held meetings with current employees wednesday and had 
sent letters to former employees 
we felt it was appropriate to let our workers know now 
bochanski said 
garabrant and rohm amp haas officials did not release a copy of 
the study saying it was only a draft 
garabrant and company officials said that based on the study 
ddt could neither be identified nor ruled out as the cause of the 
pancreatic cancer 
but they said the study was the first link between ddt which is 
known to cause cancer in laboratory animals and pancreatic cancer 
in humans garabrant ruled out other chemicals or lifestyle risks 
such as smoking 
we really have to look at this further before drawing 
conclusions about ddts link with pancreatic cancer the epas 
heier said 
the study was prompted by a 1987 report by rohm amp haas that 
found 16 cases of pancreatic cancer among the 6000 employees at 
its philadelphia plant from 194871 only about nine cases of the 
cancer would normally be expected according to bochanski 
the national rate of pancreatic cancer is about 9 cases per 
100000 people resulting in about 28100 new cases and about 
25000 deaths a year according to the american cancer society 
about 3 percent survive five years or longer 
the current study commissioned by rohm amp haas used the same 
employee population but researchers discovered 12 additional known 
cases of the cancer 
garabrant said the study examined the medical records of all 28 
employees diagnosed with pancreatic cancer and compared them to 112 
other employees matched for age sex and race who did not work 
with ddt and questioned them or surviving relatives about 
lifestyles such as smoking or diet 
rohm amp haas manufactured ddt until 1971 the company did not 
know the amount of ddt to which the employees had been exposed nor 
the length of their exposure 
an epidemiologist at fox chase cancer center thomas mason 
cautioned against reading too much into rohm amp haas early results 
ddt is stored in the bodys fat so a diet high in fat could 
affect the studys results he said he suggested that further 
research on the plants rate of pancreatic cancer and ddt examine 
the connection to diet 
bochanski said it was uncertain what the companys next step 
would be 
