britain natos most hawkish member said 
wednesday it plans to pull half its troops from west germany and 
cut its overall regular forces by 18 percent in response to a 
reduced soviet threat 
the united states announced defense reductions after last years 
democratic revolutions in eastern europe but british officials had 
cautioned against any quick decisions to slash forces 
in wednesdays announcement to the house of commons however 
defense secretary tom king acknowledged the lowering of global 
tensions 
our aim is an orderly and planned transition to the new world 
unfolding said king it is a time of opportunity and hope for 
change yet without putting at risk the safe protection of our 
country 
the moves which also call for eliminating 19 warships and 
submarines by 1995 will produce substantial savings king said 
but he gave no immediate indication of the size of the conservative 
party governments peace dividend 
king said britain will make no reductions in its nuclear 
arsenal britain still plans to modernized its submarineborne 
polaris nuclear missiles by the mid1990s with a more powerful 
trident system bought from the united states wednesdays 
announcement followed a fivemonth review of defense spending by 
prime minister margaret thatcher and a committee of top cabinet 
ministers mrs thatcher has been among the highest defense 
spenders in the western countries north atlantic treaty 
organization 
in the most dramatic proposal king said the government 
envisaged that by 1995 britain will have two rather than four 
divisions assigned to defend west germany it will also halve the 
number of air bases there 
britain has about 66700 servicemen deployed in west germany 
including the 55000member british army of the rhine they are the 
second biggest foreign military presence after the united states 
in other deep conventional arms cuts proposed by the mid1990s 
king said the royal navys submarine fleet will be reduced from 27 
to 16 threefourths of them nuclearpowered 
the british naval fleet of frigates and destroyers will be cut 
from 48 to 40 king said that move reverses a conservative party 
pledge to maintain a fleet of about 50 warships 
the number of royal air force squadrons will drop from 15 to 
about nine 
king said the reductions hinge on several factors the signing 
of an eastwest accord on conventional arms cuts final 
arrangements for german unification and the pace of withdrawal of 
soviet troops from other east european countries 
king said that by the mid1990s he envisages a british army of 
120000 down from 160000 and the royal air force with 75000 
personnel down from 89000 the royal navy and royal marines would 
be cut by only 3000 personnel to 60000 
in addition king said there will be further immediate savings 
of 11 billion from britains 386 billion defense budget for the 
fiscal year ending in march he said the army would ease back on 
recruiting and officials would retire several ships and submarines 
early 
despite his other comments king said the soviet union remained 
the mightiest military force in europe he warned that if president 
mikhail s gorbachev lost power britain could not suddenly try 
to recall its forces 
