<TEXT>
endangered florida panthers may get a 
lethal dose of mercury when they dine on raccoons that apparently 
pick up the poison by eating everglades fish scientists say 
recent laboratory analyses found significant amounts of mercury 
in the livers of raccoons captured in the eastern everglades said 
melody roelke a veterinarian for the panther recovery project 
those cats who eat these mercuryladen raccoons will pick up 
mercury but it may not be the only source roelke said tuesday 
in presenting her findings to officials from four state and federal 
agencies 
the tainted raccoons were found in the same shark river slough 
area where a 4yearold female panther known as no 27 died of 
mercury poisoning last year 
panther no 17 one of the largest and oldest known panthers at 
154 pounds and 8 to 10 years old was found dead monday its 
remains were so decomposed biologists dont think theyll be able 
to find out what killed it 
its believed only 30 to 50 panthers remain in south florida 
and they face threats ranging from habitat loss to cars on the 
roads they sometimes cross 
roelke estimated that a 75pound panther eating a 6pound 
raccoon daily from the shark river slough would accumulate a toxic 
dose of mercury in 14 weeks 
what that means is everything from uncoordination visual 
problems to seizures and death roelke said 
in the case of panther no 27 theres a good probability that 
she moved into that slough about four months prior to her death 
this is compatible with the time course for an animal eating 
nothing but raccoons every day 
officials cautioned that the data while cause for concern was 
preliminary and they said raccoons make up a main part of the 
panthers diet in only a few areas 
raccoons eat fish state health officials have warned against 
eating fish from several areas of the everglades because of the 
mercury 
