subsequent fate was not disclosed 
four cubans remain at the italian ambassadors residence 
the wave of entries at foreign embassies began july 9 after 
thousands of albanians who had sought refuge at foreign embassies 
in tirana were allowed to leave by boat to italy 
since then more than 40 cubans have sought refuge at a variety 
of embassies here according to some estimates perhaps half were 
government saboteurs on a mission to force out bona fide 
asylumseekers 
when the breakins began many analysts recalled the period 10 
years ago when 10000 crowded the peruvian embassy setting in 
motion what became the mariel boatlift over a fivemonth period 
125000 cubans left for florida 
at the time there seemed little possibility that president 
fidel castro would be toppled from power but among some western 
diplomats here there is serious question as to whether castro 
could survive a similar mass exodus now 
he is more isolated than before has far fewer allies because of 
the reforms in the soviet bloc countries and the economic situation 
has weakened marxism is almost universally discredited and food 
shortages among other problems have led to a rise in discontent 
so castro anxious to keep the problem within manageable limits 
has taken steps to discourage additional cubans from seeking asylum 
police have been deployed in large numbers at western embassies 
in addition castro has taken a hard line toward those who have 
entered embassies warning that none will be permitted to leave 
cuba in a way that circumvents normal immigrations procedures 
to some diplomats one possible solution lies in a deal under 
which the cuban asylumseekers would leave the embassies after 
receiving promises from the cuban government that no action will be 
taken against them they then would apply to leave the country 
through normal means 
ruperes suggested both sides are eager for a settlement 
on the spanish side there is serious will and i am almost 
sure there is the same on the cuban side to resolve the problem 
