<TEXT>
a nasa team investigating the flawed 
mirror that crippled the hubble space telescope started hearings 
wednesday at the plant where the mirror was made amid reports that 
tests showed a problem in 1981 
the sevenmember team led by lew allen director of nasas jet 
propulsion laboratory took testimony in secret wednesday at 
hughesdanbury optical systems inc formerly a division of 
perkinelmer corp 
interviews with employees and a review of data pertaining to the 
hubble mirrors testing and manufacturing were to continue thursday 
thomas arconti spokesman for hughesdanbury said no 
information relating to the investigation would be released while 
the probe was under way 
nasa scientists have said the flaw in the 15 billion telescope 
will cut the hubbles abilities in half and can only be partly 
corrected through a space mission scheduled for 1993 
the hubble has two mirrors a main mirror and a secondary 
mirror nasa scientists have said the problem appeared to be a 
spherical aberration a problem in the shape of the primary mirror 
the hartford courant reported wednesday that scientists may have 
discovered that flaw in may 1981 but dismissed the evidence 
because they believed it was the result of a faulty testing 
apparatus 
one source a retired perkinelmer scientist told the courant 
that the 1981 test showed a possible spherical aberration in the 
main mirror a 94inch structure that nasa had called the smoothest 
large mirror in the world 
but the scientist who spoke on condition of anonymity said the 
test results were assumed to be incorrect at the time because they 
contradicted tests done with an instrument thought to be more 
accurate 
its the smoking gun the scientist said 
perkinelmer built the mirrors between 1979 and 1982 hundreds 
of employees put in more than four million hours of work on the 
project 
the company also built part of the telescopes guidance system 
the retired scientist said that despite the 1981 test results 
additional testing did not appear necessary at the time those 
working on the mirror were under pressure to finish because of 
delays and cost overruns he added 
time and money was always a factor at that point in the 
program he said they were rushing to shut us down as fast as 
possible 
the company had originally been awarded a 63 million contract 
but cost overruns left nasa with a total bill of 451 million 
abe offner another retired perkinelmer scientist who designed 
some of the mirrors test equipment told the courant he didnt 
know of the test results and didnt think the tests were the 
problem 
why did they not do something about it offner said tuesday 
i dont know why it was not brought to my attention i would have 
said lets check it out and see what the problem is 
jeffrey clayton nasas deputy program scientist for the hubble 
project told the newspaper tuesday that nasa inspectors in danbury 
at the time probably were aware of the test results 
allen the leader of the nasa probe said im confident we 
have the ability to find the error and the results will be 
embarrassing to someone or some group but in order to get that 
answer we need people to be as candid as possible 
a statement on the teams progress would be issued from 
washington on thursday said nasa spokeswoman sarah keegan 
the perkinelmer division that built the mirrors was purchased 
last year by hughes aircraft co of california 
</TEXT>
