<TEXT>
eastern airlines and several of its top 
maintenance managers were charged wednesday with conspiring to 
falsify safety and maintenance records to avoid costly flight 
delays and cancellations 
this indictment is about failure to maintain aircraft both 
regular maintenance and parts that are faulty us attorney 
andrew j maloney said in announcing the charges the motivation 
was to get the airplanes into the air an airline only makes money 
with planes in the air 
the federal grand jury indictment is unprecedented in the 
airline industry and adds to easterns woes as it seeks to regain 
passengers build service and reorganize under federal bankruptcy 
protection after a bitter strike 
none of the alleged violations caused accidents or injuries 
authorities said 
the 60count indictment charges conspiracy to defraud the 
government wire fraud falsification of documents and obstruction 
of justice it names the airline and nine highlevel managers 
including edward upton the former vice president of maintenance 
and engineering 
until a few days ago five of the defendants were still employed 
as maintenance supervisors by the airline maloney said a 10th 
employee would be named in a separate document he said 
in a statement the miamibased airline said that during the 
last two years it had taken full corrective action under the 
scrutiny of the federal aviation administration 
today there is no question that eastern is safe eastern has 
its share of problems operating a safe airline is not one of 
them the statement said 
faa administrator james b bussey said the airline now meets the 
agencys safety standards 
we are carefully studying the indictment and if we find 
anything that gives us cause for concern we will take whatever 
action is necessary to protect the traveling public he said 
at a news conference tuesday martin shugrue appointed by a 
federal bankruptcy judge to run the airline said eastern would 
admit fraudulent maintenance and recordkeeping practices but not 
conspiracy 
he termed the purported violations ancient history said the 
problems had been corrected and insisted the airline was safe 
maloney said the violations took place from july 1985 to october 
1989 at kennedy and la guardia airports in new york hartsfield 
international airport in atlanta and eastern headquarters in miami 
the investigation began after an eastern maintenance supervisor 
voluntarily went to maloneys office and told him about alleged 
irregularities 
during the 10month investigation a federal grand jury 
uncovered a pattern of top airline managers ordering that 
maintenance not be performed on aircraft but that records be made 
to falsely show that it was maloney said 
by tampering with log books work cards and computerized 
maintenance records eastern did cause aircraft that were not 
properly maintained or repaired to fly and carry unsuspecting 
passengers the indictment said 
the charges involved critical items including radar landing 
gear automatic pilots and fuel systems maloney said 
upton and other managers pressured supervisors and mechanics 
to sign off on airplanes that had not had their regular maintenance 
or corrective maintenance in order to get the plane in the air or 
perhaps risk their jobs maloney said 
among the irregularities cited by maloney were a failure to 
properly remove accumulated water from fuel tanks the water can 
freeze at high altitudes and clog fuel lines and makes fuel gauges 
read high 
in atlanta he said workers installed defective or untested 
cockpit instruments to make it appear that corrective repairs had 
been made 
if convicted on all counts eastern faces a maximum fine of 30 
million each individual defendant faces up to five years in prison 
and fines up to 250000 for each count 
this case is not about money or fines this case is about 
deterrence and a very important area of public safety maloney 
said this is one of those indictments that is trying to send a 
message to the entire airlines industry 
easterns employees went on strike march 4 1989 and the 
company filed for bankruptcy protection five days later pilots and 
flight attendants quit the strike several months later but the 
mechanics remain on strike 
shugrue said eastern expected to turn a profit in 1991 it is 
projected to lose about 500 million this year after an 852 
million loss in 1989 
maloney said prosecutors had no evidence of improprieties at the 
airline since shugrue assumed control 
