<TEXT>
the senate formally denounced sen dave 
durenberger on wednesday for knowingly and willfully violating 
its rules and ordered him to make restitution of up to 123000 for 
money he received improperly 
durenberger rminn made no attempt to fight the vote to 
denounce him speaking in a quiet voice he pledged to strive to 
become first a better man and then a better senator 
the somber judgment marked the 24th time in 201 years that the 
senate disciplined one of its own the vote was 960 and after 
rendering their verdict many senators lined up to shake 
durenbergers hand some embracing him 
durenberger and fellow minnesota republican rudy boschwitz voted 
present 
durenberger was disciplined for violating senate speaking fee 
and gift limits misleading the senate on real estate transactions 
involving his minneapolis condominium and converting a campaign 
contribution to personal use 
sen howell heflin dala chairman of the senate ethics 
committee set the stage for the dramatic vote when he solemnly 
accused durenberger who watched from a frontrow desk of 
violating his public trust 
the evidence of knowing and willful misconduct is clear and 
convincing and far more troubling than sen durenbergers admitted 
negligence lack of wisdom or asserted misplaced reliance on 
others heflin said 
the committee findings will be referred to the federal election 
commission and justice department for further investigation but 
there have been no allegations of criminal wrongdoing 
a tense calm hung over the crowded senate gallery as tourists 
and other passersby listened as senator after senator stood to 
praise durenberger for his legislative accomplishments even as they 
were condemning him for his ethical lapses 
no one in this chamber is approaching this vote lightly 
said sen orrin g hatch rutah the stones of denouncement are 
easier to cast than they are to retrieve 
heflin a former alabama supreme court justice said there was 
convincing evidence that sen durenberger knowingly and willfully 
engaged in a pattern of unethical misconduct which violated 
statutes rules and standards of conduct 
the ethics committee said durenberger should reimburse the 
senate 29050 plus interest for improper reimbursements he 
received while staying in his minneapolis condominium during 
official trips from 198389 
it also said he should pay 93730 less state and federal taxes 
previously paid for speaking fees he improperly kept during 1985 
and 1986 
the fees were for 113 speeches durenberger said were promotions 
for his books on health care and defense issues the committee 
concluded they were normal honoraria speeches subject to senate 
limits 
durenberger whose political fortunes have suffered at home 
told the senate just before heflin spoke that he would not contest 
the committees recommendation and earlier agreed to make 
restitution 
durenberger sat at a desk at the front of the senate chamber 
listening to the proceedings with his hand on his chin 
i ask your forgiveness durenberger told his colleagues 
after the vote for future challenges i need your friendship 
he called the experience a costly education 
as for the future i would ask only that i be judged not 
necessarily by what i say but what i do he said financial 
restitution is only a beginning 
at a news conference after the senate vote durenberger 
reiterated his pledge to become a better senator 
durenberger a 12year senate veteran was elected to fill the 
unexpired term of the late sen hubert humphrey he does not face 
reelection until 1994 
the end of the durenberger case will allow the ethics committee 
to concentrate on pending investigations of six senators including 
five who received donations from savings and loan figure charles 
keating and interceded with regulators on his behalf 
in a case involving another lawmaker the house ethics committee 
has proposed that rep barney frank dmass be reprimanded for 
improperly using his office to help a male prostitute action on 
that recommendation is expected this week 
several republican colleagues said they believed durenbergers 
judgment had been impaired by tragedies problems he discussed 
during a june ethics committee hearing 
the senators first wife died of breast cancer 20 years ago and 
durenberger said he was seeing a marriage counselor because his 
second marriage was in trouble the couple remains married 
he also said he was affected by severe financial problems 
caused in part by educational expenses for his four sons 
the chairman of the senate republican caucus said durenbergers 
committee assignments and other duties would not be affected by the 
senate action the major impact on durenberger is the political 
fallout in minnesota where some newspapers have called on him to 
resign 
seven members of the senate have been censured since the first 
recorded case in 1811 one democratic sen herman e talmadge of 
georgia was denounced in 1979 
fifteen have been expelled the most serious punishment 
the last major ethics case involved new jersey democrat harrison 
a williams jr who resigned in 1982 as his colleagues were about 
to oust him 
in addition to the excess speaking fees the committee found 
that durenberger 
violated senate rules and the ethics in government act when he 
failed to disclose on public forms travel reimbursements he 
received from 43 organizations in 1985 and 1986 
broke the rules by converting a campaign contribution of 5000 
to his personal use 
exceeded a rule limiting the value of gifts to 100 annually 
when he accepted free limousine service during 1985 and 1986 from 
people or groups interested in legislation he used the limousines 
to see his marriage counselor in concord mass 
conceived a partnership arrangement for his condominium solely 
to enable him to claim reimbursement for overnight stays 
structured a purported sale of the condominium to a friends 
company and knowingly participated in back dating the transaction 
to justify claims for reimbursement 
not voting wednesday were republican sens larry pressler of 
south dakota and malcolm wallop of wyoming 
