<TEXT>
two weeks of rain helped save some of the 
southeasts parched soybean cotton and peanut crops but farm 
experts warned that without more rain soon disastrous losses are 
still likely 
the national weather service said significant rainfall for the 
region is unlikely in the next two weeks although spotty afternoon 
and evening thundershowers will continue 
six weeks of hot dry weather with temperatures hovering around 
100 degrees destroyed corn in georgia and north carolina and 
threatened peanuts and soybeans throughout the region 
soybeans are vital to farmers in tennessee and about half the 
nations peanuts are grown in alabama and in georgia where they 
are the main crop 
larry snipes of the georgia agricultural statistics service said 
crop conditions are improving after storms over the last two weeks 
raised the months rainfall totals to almost normal 408 inches 
in july officials said parts of the state were 6 inches below 
normal for the year 
were a lot more optimistic now than we were two weeks ago 
said carl cross a statistician for the north carolina department 
of agriculture if we get normal precipitation for the remainder 
of the season we could still have some good crops before the end 
of the season 
in north carolina june rainfall averaged about 3 inches below 
normal south carolina was 2 to 5 inches below and tennessee had 
accumulated a 914inch shortage since jan 1 
the rain came too late for corn the georgia farm bureau said 
100 percent of the states dry land corn crop was lost and 
irrigated production a tiny portion of the crop would be 
reduced because of poor pollination and heat stress 
cross said that in north carolina corn also was in the early 
stages of pollination when hot dry weather arrived causing 
reduced yields and in some areas the loss of the entire crop 
but in tennessee the wet spring may have saved corn from the 
dry summer soggy conditions in april and may delayed the planting 
period meaning corn hadnt reached critical growth stages when the 
dry spell began said usda statistician ron brantner 
