<TEXT>
marshall bitkower a former prosecutor had 
built a lucrative private law practice he had a nice home in the 
san fernando valley he drove a rollsroyce 
and then something happened 
bitkower started borrowing money from client trust funds he 
was arrested and served time for drunken driving in 1982 to avoid 
disbarment he voluntarily resigned from the practice of law 
what happened to bitkower was cocaine his story it appears is 
headed for a happy ending he has been straight for eight years now 
but the state bar of california says there are thousands of 
other lawyers who come to court each day drunk or high and the bar 
which normally keeps its members personal problems private is 
going public with a highprofile campaign to battle substance abuse 
among attorneys 
if youre in a highstress occupation substance abuse is 
greater said state bar president alan rothenberg 
the legal profession is certainly a highstress profession if 
youre doing trial work thats high stress if youre in a 
criminal trial your clients life or death is at stake thats 
about as stressful as anything 
surveys conducted by the state bars in washington and oregon 
indicate 15 percent to 18 percent of lawyers are alcoholics the 
state bar of texas estimates the incidence of substance abuse among 
lawyers may be 20 percent twice as high as that of the general 
population 
the american bar association says 86 percent of state bar 
associations have some sort of program for impaired attorneys 
there are about 100 active programs across the united states 
the aba launched a commission on impaired attorneys in 1988 to 
serve as a clearinghouse and network for programs like texas 
lawyers assistance program which has offered confidential 
counseling since 1982 
the california bar is the nations largest 
if you figure that one out of 10 americans has a substance 
abuse problem and there are 122000 lawyers in the california bar 
then as many as 12000 may have a problem said rothenberg 
even if its only 5 percent thats 6100 lawyers and thats too 
many 
but california with more attorneys than any state and a fair 
share of celebrity multimillionaire lawyers has been slow to 
voluntarily tarnish its public image rothenberg acknowledges that 
going public was a tough decision 
we finally decided we had no choice he said the bigger 
risk was not to do something 
the new program involves referral to treatment programs and 
offers insurance coverage to lawyers for such treatment 
law schools will be urged to include a substance abuse course in 
their curriculums the bars mandatory continuing legal education 
also will require attorneys to take a course on the subject in 
order to keep their licenses to practice law firms will be 
encouraged to address the problem with programs in their own 
offices the bar also has a 24hour hotline for attorneys needing 
referrals to drug and alcohol programs 
meanwhile a task force is gathering statistics on how many 
lawyers actually have drug and alcohol problems 
lawyers who turn to drugs and alcohol usually get into trouble 
with their clients and often face arrest and disciplinary 
proceedings 
we find that in a lot of cases the person suffering from 
substance abuse is not handling business as they should said 
bill davis the bars assistant chief trial counsel who handles 
complaints about attorneys lodged by the public if the substance 
abuse gets worse ultimately theyre stealing clients funds to 
support their habit 
that scenario in fact is what happened to bitkower 
i was under a lot of stress he recalls of the early 1980s 
when his practice was thriving somebody recommended cocaine to 
calm me down and help me deal with the stress and aggravation 
the result was disastrous 
it ruined my life he said it almost killed me i lost 
everything i ended up sleeping on a mattress in hermosa beach and 
hitchhiking from a nice family man in the valley who had it all i 
went to having nothing 
about that time he said i woke up one day and decided i 
either was going to die or get help he checked into a sixweek 
drug treatment program at st johns hospital in santa monica 
where he kicked his cocaine habit 
you can come back after sliding so far down he said 
bitkower 47 has put his marriage and family back together 
works as an administrator at a beverly hills law firm and recently 
was recommended by the california bar for reinstatement as a lawyer 
bitkower joined alcoholics anonymous but he also credited ted 
cohen a family friend who had begun helping lawyers with alcohol 
problems 
cohen himself an attorney and recovering alcoholic introduced 
bitkower to a group called the other bar an offshoot of alcoholics 
anonymous the other bar offers lawyers and judges the help of 
their peers in a safe haven where their problems need not be 
publicized and where others understand it has helped some 4000 
lawyers deal with alcohol and drug addiction cohen said 
most lawyers now seeking help from the other bar are young and 
their addiction is to cocaine cohen said 
with anybody under 40 its drugs he said the young kids 
are not alcoholics 
cohen started the group in 1972 when his own drinking caught up 
with him he was convicted of stealing a small amount of money in 
an insurance scam and ultimately served six months in a prison work 
furlough program fellow aa members visited him and the idea of 
the other bar was born 
cohen who resumed practicing law in 1974 now splits his time 
between legal cases and the other bar he also is a member of the 
aba commission 
you try to give back what was given to you he said 
