<TEXT>
whatever congress decides on the 1990 farm 
bill cant begin to settle the basic question of whether 
agricultural subsidies should exist at all are they justified or 
simply an expensive ripoff 
farm bills for decades have been complicated vehicles for 
agricultural special interests they are increasingly expensive 
costing 50 billion or more just for commodity supports over a 
fiveyear span 
defenders say such expense is necessary to preserve the heart 
and soul of us agriculture the family farmer and to guarantee 
consumers a fair shake at the supermarket 
some critics say federal farm subsidies are really welfare and 
that the larger producers should be excluded but lawyers michael 
r mcleod and john harris defend the system 
mcleod is a former general counsel for the senate agriculture 
committee and harris was associate general counsel for the 
agriculture department 
to say farmers who participate in farm programs are on welfare 
has as much validity as saying newspapers receiving a subsidy 
through the postal service are on welfare or that homeowners who 
use the mortgage interest deduction are on welfare mcleod and 
harris say in their agricultural law letter 
the two analysts commented on proposals to restrict federal farm 
subsidies to smaller producers and eliminating the payments to big 
farmers 
any farm program that confers benefits on producers of a 
particular commodity is fair game in an urban congress they 
said however it is not fair to try to bring down the entire 
federal farm structure by making it unworkable 
moreover said mcleod and harris legislation to impose 
eligibility tests for farmers comparable to the means tests for 
welfare recipients fails to recognize the broader implications of 
agricultural programs 
consumers they said have had access to an abundant supply of 
reasonably priced food year after year because of a sound and 
stable agricultural economy that at least partially depends on 
these very farm programs 
james bovard of the cato institute an independent public policy 
research organization thinks that argument is a worn piece of 
barnyard debris that should have been tossed aside years ago 
one of the features of farm programs since the early 1930s has 
been the limitation of production through acreage controls soil 
banks quotas price support incentives or other devices 
even so farm production has generally outpaced demands except 
during years when exports have drawn off surpluses and production 
suffered from bad weather 
direct subsidies are paid to farmers who cooperate in the 
various commodity programs other benefits are in the form of 
credit guarantees and technical assistance 
whether direct or indirect bovard says there is no difference 
a subsidy is a subsidy 
the only way to successfully reform farm programs is to 
abolish them bovard said in a recent policy paper we cannot 
compete with either foreign farmers or foreign farm subsidies by 
shutting down american farms 
in bovards view farm productivity has always advanced faster 
than politicians understanding of the problem 
bovard said that in the 1980s taxpayers and consumers shelled 
out 260 billion to support americas farmers farm programs he 
said currently cost around 20 billion a year plus 10 billion in 
higher food prices 
almost all of that cost is a dead loss to the american 
economy he said yet the agriculture department is rewarding 
farmers for idling almost 60 million acres this year the 
equivalent of shutting down all the cropland in california 
colorado kentucky louisiana montana and wisconsin 
there is nothing to show for the outlays except idled acres 
polluted groundwater and richer farmers bovard said 
when usda and farmstate members of congress talk about costs of 
farm programs they usually refer only to the direct cost of price 
support operations bovard said that is often less than half of the 
total government spending on farmers 
for example he said in 1990 the usda expects to spend less 
than 81 billion on price support and deficiency payments to 
farmers 
bovard said the estimate overlooks defaults in export credit 
guarantees bonuses to exporters to subsidize commodity sales 
overseas food for peace farmers home administration operations 
assistance by the soil conservation service crop insurance 
subsidies free advice from the extension service and agricultural 
research 
thus while congressmen talk of farm subsidies amounting to 8 
billion taxpayers are actually liable for over 25 billion in 
spending and loan guarantees he said 
bovard added it is difficult to know exactly how many usda 
loans and loan guarantees will be defaulted on but if the nation 
has learned anything from the savingsandloan crisis it should 
recognize that federal guarantees are often the most expensive 
government programs of all 
a mainstay of bovards argument is that the average fulltime 
farmer is a wealthy individual and doesnt need government help 
bovard said many economists agree a farm should have gross sales 
of more than 100000 a year to be viable those he said are 
fulltime farmers who account for 80 percent to 90 percent of total 
farm income in 1980 there were 271000 farms in the 100000plus 
category by 1988 there were 323000 
some farmaid advocates also count farms in the 
40000to99000 category as fulltime others however say many 
of those are underemployed in much of the year or are inefficient 
the average net worth of us families in 1986 was 78734 per 
household in contrast he said the average fulltime farmer as of 
dec 31 1988 had a net worth of more than 1 million 
some liberals advocate continuing government aid to small 
farmers only but even parttime farmers are far wealthier than the 
average american family bovard said farmers in the 40000 to 
99999 sales class have a net worth of 426487 more than five 
times that of the average american family 
