<TEXT>
more than a year after revealing a probe of 
the new york commodities pits federal futures regulators have 
charged four brokers with fraud in handling customer orders 
the commodity futures trading commission accused the four and a 
firm owned by one of them of noncompetitively executing crude oil 
futures trades for customers on the floor of the new york 
mercantile exchange in lower manhattan 
the four all registered with the cftc as floor brokers were 
identified as douglas m friedman of forest hills queens ny 
michael s pomerantz scarsdale ny lawrence a beck fort lee 
nj john j king old bridge nj 
also named in the ninecount administrative complaint disclosed 
tuesday was msp trading inc a firm owned by pomerantz 
pomerantz king and beck were accused of deceiving and 
defrauding customers by taking their orders to buy or sell and then 
taking the opposite position at the customers expense 
allegedly with friedmans help the moves would violate cftc rules 
that require a trader to submit customer orders to the general 
marketplace 
the investigation is continuing said dennis klejna 
director of the cftcs enforcement division he said further 
charges were certainly possible 
pomerantzs lawyer barry mandel and kings lawyer ira lee 
sorkin both in new york said they had not seen the cftc complaint 
and therefore could not comment lawyers for the other defendants 
were not in their offices when called for comment tuesday night 
the investigation came to light in may 1989 when the government 
revealed it was conducting criminal and civil investigations of 
alleged illegal trading at four new york commodities exchanges 
the cftc complaint alleged that the other three used friedman 
who trades primarily for his own account to circumvent cftc rules 
between july and december 1988 
if an administrative law judge rules in favor of the cftc the 
defendants could be subject to penalties ranging from suspension of 
trading privileges to fines up to 100000 per violation 
the investigations are unrelated to a longstanding probe of 
chicagos commodity markets that yielded indictments against 48 
