<TEXT>
congress is moving steadily toward passing a 
fiveyear farm bill that generally maintains current law and 
preserves most of the governments farm support systems including 
the hotly debated sugar program 
during a marathon session that began tuesday morning and lasted 
until nearly midnight the senate defeated one challenge after 
another to the bill worked out by its agriculture committee 
the price support system protecting honey producers is the only 
program that has been eliminated so far opponents of the peanut 
program were mounting their offensive today 
the house also was protecting the work of its committee as it 
defeated efforts to change the dairy and sugar programs 
opponents of the present sugar program wanted to change the 
support price from 18 cents a pound to 16 cents a proposal also 
supported by the bush administration 
that reduction would have brought the support for sugar more in 
line with other government farm programs easing the struggle 
between midwestern grain farmers and the betterrewarded sugar beet 
producers threatening to buy them out amendment supporters said 
wheat farmers and barley farmers support the sugar program 
sen bill bradley dnj said sarcastically they would like to 
have one like it 
rep thomas downey dny called sugar producers the most 
pampered farmers in america and the most profitable 
bradley also said the quota system used to control the amount of 
foreign sugar sold in the united states hurts poor latin american 
countries receiving foreign aid 
he said some of those countries are trying to find alternatives 
to coca the raw material for cocaine and would benefit from more 
open markets in the united states 
the coca price is below the breakeven point said bradley 
this is an opportunity for us to begin to wean some of these 
countries from coca production into other crops particularly 
sugar 
supporters said the program was needed to preserve american jobs 
and provide price stability they said that even if the support 
price were reduced consumers would not see any difference in the 
price of products containing sugar 
to say this can be passed on to the american housewife is the 
wildest speculation said rep arlan stangeland rminn all 
this will do is put more money in the hands of the manufacturer who 
is using sugar 
an amendment by sen tom daschle dsd to increase target 
prices on wheat and feed grains for smaller producers lost 7224 
daschle said it was needed to keep 500000 family farms from 
going out of business during the fiveyear life of the bill it 
would have put target prices on a twotier system in an effort to 
get more money for small and mediumsized farms without going over 
budget 
for example instead of freezing the target price on wheat at 4 
a bushel as called for in the bill daschle would have farmers 
receiving 410 a bushel for the first 12500 bushels of wheat and 
340 for every subsequent bushel 
similar adjustments would be made for corn oats sorghum and 
barley which also are frozen at current levels in the bill 
opponents of the amendment including agriculture committee 
chairman patrick leahy dvt said it would destroy the compromise 
worked out by the panel possibly preventing passage of the whole 
bill 
in other action the senate 
approved an amendment that prevents fruits vegetables 
potatoes and edible beans from being grown on acreage that is 
covered by the flexibility provisions of the bills subsidy program 
defeated a plan to allow foreign vessels to be used if no 
usflagged vessels are available for food aid shipments to 
foreign countries 
the house meanwhile 
defeated an amendment that would have allowed the agriculture 
department to reduce the milk price support level if surpluses 
exceeded 5 billion pounds in any year 
approved a provision to prevent states from imposing any 
surcharge for milk processing greater than the federal governments 
voted to allow grazing on land that is set aside under the 
cotton acreage reduction program 
approved disaster payments to cotton producers who are 
prevented from planting because of indian water rights disputes 
