warner deal in a way that required no shareholder vote and got the 
delaware supreme courts blessing in a ruling july 24 1989 
as a result paramount never got the chance to take its offer 
directly to times stockholders many still resent that 
we would have preferred that they would have accepted 
paramounts offer said kyle krueger portfolio manager for eagle 
asset management in st petersburg fla which now owns 163 
percent of time warners stock 
but he doesnt blame time warner management for the companys 
current low price we think they are doing fairly well he said 
time warner executives say the companys stock price reflects 
the markets distaste for companies with debt and its disfavor for 
those in the cable and entertainment industries in particular 
they argue time warner can handle its debt time warners 
magazine music film book tv production and cable television 
businesses are generating more than enough cash to meet debt 
payments over the next few years they say 
securities analysts generally agree that the company will 
generate 21 billion to 25 billion in cash flow a year while 
interest and preferred stock payments will require about 13 
billion a year through 1992 
but in 1993 the company is due to reduce its debt by 2 
billion mcalpine and others feel the company will have to either 
sell assets or take on partners in joint ventures to raise money by 
that date 
mcalpine also said the company has 3 billion in investments 
that could be sold to reduce debt these include shares of 
companies such as hasbro atari and turner broadcasting systems 
inc real estate in burbank calif and minority interests in 
assorted cable system operators 
time warners cochief executives steven j ross and nicholas 
j nicholas jr told analysts in may that they are looking for 
partners who can give the company access to new makets or who will 
pay handsomely for a minority stake in various time warner 
operations 
in the meantime ross and nicholas appear determined to run the 
company as if there were no 108 billion debt 
peter appert media analyst for cj lawrence morgan grenfell 
inc wrote after the may meeting that while the company was aware 
of wall streets concerns with its high debt level managements 
focus appears to be on expanding the business first and lowering 
the debt levels second 
time warner has made a number of strategic deals over the past 
few months 
it bought lane publishing a california magazine publisher for 
about 180 million in cash and stock senior magazine executives 
hope to use lane as a springboard for regional publishing ventures 
in the west and far east 
in april the company paid 195 million for a 195 percent 
stake in six flags corp which runs seven amusement parks and may 
offer a wider outlet for the warner bros cast of cartoon 
characters such as bugs bunny and daffy duck 
time warner spent 133 million in march for a 25 percent stake 
in a cellular radio venture with price communications it offers an 
opportunity to get a close look at a new line of business 
it entered a joint venture for a scandinavian pay tv service 
and is helping build the first modern movie theaters in the soviet 
union both markets offer appealing growth potential 
its most controversial move to date was a tentative agreement to 
guarantee 650 million in loans for pathe communications incs 
12 billion bid for mgmua communications inc 
the deal alarmed some analysts who felt time warner could not 
afford the extra debt but time warner executives said the risk was 
well worth it because its loan guarantee would have been secured by 
the united artists film library that they said was worth much more 
than 650 million 
the issue has evidently become moot as the pact between pathe 
and time fell apart amid an exchange of lawsuits before any loans 
were arranged 
from an outsiders perspective maybe it was better that they 
didnt get involved said edward atorino media analyst for 
salomon brothers inc 
time warner also is investing millions in its core businesses 
it launched a magazine entertainment weekly which some analysts 
say could lose 60 million before turning profitable and a cable 
network the comedy channel 
the company also has cut back since time obtained control of 
warner last july it sold the textbook company scott foresman and 
co for 448 million last december its southern progress corp 
suspended publication of moneylosing southpoint magazine a 
regional magazine in may 
nonetheless the company says the diversity of its businesses 
which run from time and fortune magazines and bookofthemonth 
club to music from pasula abdul and movies like batman and 
driving miss daisy insulate it against reversals in any one 
business 
gordon crawford senior vice president at the research arm of 
capital group inc the single largest time warner stockholder with 
an 8 percent stake said company management is doing fine and the 
market will eventually realize it 
their actions illustrate they are going to continue running 
the company in an aggressive fashion with a longterm point of 
view he said 
