<DOCNO> AP900725-0237 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when the multibilliondollar fight for time inc 
landed in the delaware courts last year everyone who followed the 
case knew there was more at stake than just the outcome of a 
takeover battle 
they were right the legal precedent that emerged strengthened 
the takeover defenses of some of the nations biggest firms and 
became a model for laws in other states 
when the ohio legislature passed a new antitakeover bill in 
april lawmakers included a provision that has become known as the 
time warner amendment the selection of a time frame for the 
achievement of corporate goals shall be the responsibility of the 
directors 
the provision codifies the delaware supreme courts ruling that 
boards of directors are not under a duty to put aside their 
longterm goals in favor of a takeover bid that would give 
stockholders more money for their shares now 
leigh trevor a member of the ohio state bar association who 
lobbied for the amendments passage said he and other corporate 
lawyers wanted to remove debate over that subject in court 
should an ohio company find itself in a situation similar to times 
in march 1989 time and warner communications inc announced 
plans to merge in a stock swap valued at 18 billion then in 
june three weeks before shareholders were to vote on the deal 
paramount communications inc launched a hostile 107 billion bid 
for time alone 
time responded by beginning its own 14 billion tender offer for 
warner paramount raised its bid to 122 billion and the companies 
went to court in delaware where all three were incorporated 
paramount argued that the time board should be forced to 
seriously consider its bid which would give shareholders immediate 
cash instead of the future profits promised by time and warner 
meanwhile the wouldbe merger partners contended that their 
plans which culminated two years of negotiations should not 
have to be shunted aside just because a third party had put a 
higher offer on the table 
in july delaware chancery court judge william t allen and then 
the state supreme court upheld the right of the time board to 
proceed with the combination with warner and the creation of time 
warner inc 
in a written decision issued in february supreme court justice 
henry r horsey said a board of directors is not under any 
per se duty to maximize shareholder value in the shortterm even in 
the context of a takeover 
legal scholars viewed the ruling as strengthening the hand of 
directors in takeover battles 
the decision automatically added protection to other companies 
incorporated in delaware home to many of the countrys biggest 
firms including about half the fortune 500 other states look to 
delaware for guidance on corporate law issues so ohio included the 
delaware ruling in its statutes 
we wanted to make it crystal clear if it is not already clear 
enough the time frame for achieving corporate objectives is a 
board decision said trevor a partner with the law firm jones 
day reavis amp pogue in cleveland 
critics of antitakeover statutes tend to view laws such as the 
new ohio provision as a means for entrenching management 
but its supporters say this was no kneejerk reaction to the 
delaware ruling 
if we cannot have the opportunity for longterm planning in 
publicly held american companies we put ourselves at a 
disadvantage with foreign competitors whose legal systems do 
provide adequate time for longterm planning and implementation of 
longterm plans trevor said 
we have been handing to our international competitors an 
advantage because they can look out at the horizon and over the 
hill and we cant he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

