<DOCNO> AP900725-0242 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
massachusetts highest court threw out parts of a 
lawsuit wednesday against a tobacco company whose cigarettes were 
bought by minors but allowed some claims to continue 
the supreme judicial court granted summary judgment in favor of 
philip morris cos inc dismissing claims that the company should 
be held liable for the fact that convenience stores sold cigarettes 
to the two plaintiffs theresa kyte and sean cann 
but the court said the plaintiffs could pursue their claims that 
the company engaged in a deceptive act in violation of state 
consumer protection laws the court also declined to dismiss a 
claim that the company breached an implied warranty that its 
products were safe 
a middlesex county superior court judge had denied the companys 
motions for summary judgment 
you only need one claim to win said edward greer an 
attorney representing the plaintiffs 
but hadrian katz an attorney for philip morris said the 
courts decision effectively wiped out the plaintiffs case 
theres nothing left he said 
tobacco liability cases have been brought against cigarette 
companies in the past but rarely have met success 
in 1988 a federal jury in new jersey awarded the first damages 
against a cigarette company giving 400000 to a man whose wife 
died of lung cancer but an appeals court overturned the award this 
year and ordered a new trial 
in boston this year a federal jury found american tobacco co 
should not be held liable for the cancer death of a cambridge man 
greer said unlike the previous cases his case focuses on minors 
who do not have the same ability as adults to gather information 
and make decisions 
kyte of waltham started smoking at age 12 and cann of 
brookline at age 15 each smoked marlboro and parliament 
cigarettes made by philip morris 
they claim they repeatedly bought the cigarettes at convenience 
stores even though state law prohibits selling tobacco to minors 
in their suit they said the company conspired to sell the 
cigarettes to minors through the convenience stores 
but the high court rejected the argument 
we have accepted the principle that in particular 
circumstances a supplier may be liable for harm caused after the 
supplier knowingly placed property in the hands of an incompetent 
person the court said 
our cases have not however held a manufacturer of a product 
liable in negligence simply because some third party unlawfully 
placed that product in the hands of a minor and as a result the 
minor or some other person was harmed the decision said 
in a dissenting opinion chief justice paul liacos said the 
plaintiffs raised legitimate issues and should have been allowed to 
present more evidence to support their claims 
the court allowed two other claims to proceed one is that 
philip morris violated state consumer protection laws through a 
pattern and practice of sales to minors greer said he said he 
would show that philip morris profits from sales to minors and 
targets its advertising toward young consumers 
the second claim accuses the company of breaching an implied 
warranty that its products are fit for intended use free from 
defect safe to consume and noncarcinogenic and nonaddictive 
to make this case the plaintiffs claim a design defect 
specifically with marlboro and parliament cigarettes rather than 
claiming all cigarettes are inherently defective 
philip morris katz said the claims of unique design defects 
were nonsense 
</TEXT>
