<TEXT>
a meeting of senior trade negotiators is expected 
to end thursday with agreement on the need for intense efforts to 
overcome barriers in crucial talks aimed at a more open global 
economy 
but the outcome of the fourday meeting leaves rifts between the 
united states and the european community and between 
industrialized countries and the third world 
david woods spokesman for the general agreement on tariffs and 
trade said wednesday that the meeting would likely endorse a 
package of proposals aimed at liberalizing trade in 15 key areas 
however he said a number of highlevel officials attending the 
105nation trade negotiations committee meeting had voiced 
disappointment that more progress had not been made on narrowing 
differences 
the proposals are described as profile accords full 
agreements are meant to be finalized at the start of december when 
the uruguay round of trade talks concludes 
the aim of the negotiations launched in 1986 is to reduce 
barriers to trade and set new standards in important areas such as 
banking services many countries have warned that failure of the 
talks will lead to a dangerous surge of protectionism 
but the profiles demonstrate how much work remains little 
more than four months before the deadline 
the proposal on liberalizing trade in textiles for example 
includes conflicting policy options backed by the united states 
the ec and third world textile exporters 
the text on intellectual property rights such as patents also 
reflects the same threeway split 
a compromise document on agriculture lays out clear proposals 
for cutting domestic farm supports and import barriers and says 
export subsidies should be reduced most of all 
but the united states and agricultural exporters like australia 
still insist on the elimination of export subsidies while the ec 
has made it plain it will defend their use 
woods said the meeting had met the endofjuly target for 
profile accords even though some countries may not agree that 
what we have achieved are satisfactory final profiles 
he said the final session thursday was expected to agree on a 
way to intensify the negotiations the meeting comprised mainly of 
officials just below ministerial rank was originally scheduled to 
last until friday 
it had been widely billed as a chance to boost progress in the 
most contentious areas 
chief ec negotiator hugo paemen told a press conference that 
senior officials were likely to travel to geneva for another 
meeting oct 8 and then be on permanent standby until the 
december ministerial gathering in brussels 
he described the package of proposals as a strong basis to 
start from 
paemens optimism contrasted with formal statements from 
developing countries brazil colombia mexico and china were among 
those criticizing lack of headway in efforts to reduce import 
duties and open markets 
the united states australia and canada all voiced concern in 
speeches tuesday 
